{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d4952c49-260a-472a-bfe0-37b7b4c8d3a6","content":"The template has the basic required fields but has a few gaps before it's truly NuGet-publish-ready:\n\n**Issues to fix:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/editor support.\n2. **Missing `description`** — Critical for discoverability on NuGet and in `dotnet new list`.\n3. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Needed so `dotnet new install`/`uninstall`/update work cleanly across versions (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n\n**Nice to have:**\n\n4. **Missing `defaultName`** — Controls the fallback project name (e.g., `\"defaultName\": \"WebApi1\"`).\n5. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`: `true`** — Standard for project templates.\n6. **`Framework` symbol** isn't wired to anything (no `replaces` mapping), so selecting a framework won't actually change the generated project.\n\n**Verdict:** Not ready yet. At minimum, add `description` and `groupIdentity` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2841a7b6-9f38-4d3e-bed3-d3fa88edf838","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages so templates can be grouped properly. Without it, updates/uninstalls may not work cleanly.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Works with groupIdentity for versioning. Not critical but recommended.\n\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Good practice for project templates, though optional.\n\nThe core metadata like identity, name, shortName, and sourceName are all present and look solid. Tags include the required language and type fields. I'm noticing the Framework symbol is defined but doesn't appear to be connected to any actual replacements or conditional logic in the template structure.\n\nThe real gaps that matter for publishing are the missing `description` field—templates without descriptions won't show up meaningfully in `dotnet new list` or NuGet search results—and the missing `groupIdentity`, which is important for how NuGet handles updates and package management. The `$schema` reference would also be good to include. The `defaultName` would be a nice touch for user experience, but it's not critical.","outputTokens":760,"requestId":"FBCC:2C695B:D0B16B:F19F5B:69FE86E2"},"id":"14c75866-88eb-4008-b534-ca63a49e826c","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:59:31.175Z","parentId":"3b088386-bc08-4007-8aee-5b0e8d8990af"}
